    cellular: { title: "Forensic Nursing Principles", content: "Forensic nursing integrates nursing science with forensic science and criminal justice principles to provide specialized care to patients who are victims or perpetrators of violence, trauma, or abuse. The forensic nurse examines patients at the intersection of healthcare and the legal system, collecting and preserving evidence while providing compassionate, trauma-informed care. Key principles include: chain of custody (documenting every person who handles evidence from collection through courtroom presentation), evidence preservation (using proper collection techniques, labeling, storage, and documentation to maintain forensic integrity), mandatory reporting obligations (abuse, neglect, gunshot wounds, communicable diseases as required by jurisdiction), and objective clinical documentation (recording facts without interpretation or judgment). The Sexual Assault Nurse Examiner (SANE) is a specialized forensic nursing role that performs comprehensive forensic examinations of sexual assault victims, collecting DNA evidence, documenting injuries, providing prophylactic medications, and offering crisis support. Forensic documentation differs from standard nursing documentation: it must be thorough enough to withstand legal scrutiny, use body maps to document injury locations, describe injuries using precise medical terminology (ecchymosis rather than 'bruise,' laceration rather than 'cut'), and avoid subjective interpretation." },
